      "content": "A fixed-rate mortgage is the type of loan where your monthly payment stays the same throughout the life of the loan, while an adjustable-rate mortgage (ARM) has an interest rate that can change after an initial fixed period. In your 5-year window, an ARM's payment is likely to remain stable if the rate doesn't adjust yet, but if rates do go up, your monthly payment could increase significantly—sometimes by 20% to 50% or more depending on how much the rate hikes. \n\nThis volatility is why many people choose a fixed-rate mortgage for long-term stability, whereas an ARM might offer lower initial rates that could become a financial burden if market rates rise sharply. Always consult a financial advisor to understand how current market trends might impact your specific situation.",
